            <fr:title text="Rules">Rules</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>To get to rules, let's start with the idea of a <html:em>rule instance</html:em>:</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>4</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>7</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/0069/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>0069</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/lectures/0069/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Rule instance, obeying a rule instance">Rule instance, obeying a rule instance</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>A <html:strong>rule instance</html:strong> has two parts: first, a set of arguments (called the <html:strong>premise-arguments</html:strong>), and second, a particular argument (called the <html:strong>conclusion-argument</html:strong>).
A rule instance is written with a horizontal line, with the premise-arguments occurring above the line and the  conclusion-argument below it.</html:p>
                <html:p>For examples:
<html:ul><html:li><html:p>The rule instance with the single premise-argument <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \;/\; q]]></fr:tex> and the conclusion-argument <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \land  q \;/\; r]]></fr:tex> is written as:</html:p>

<html:p><fr:resource hash="859f4110b517626de6dba626bb89e1d1"><fr:resource-content><html:img src="/lectures/859f4110b517626de6dba626bb89e1d1.svg" /></fr:resource-content><fr:resource-source type="latex" part="preamble"><![CDATA[\usepackage {ebproof}]]></fr:resource-source><fr:resource-source type="latex" part="body"><![CDATA[
\begin {prooftree}
\hypo {p \;/\; q}
\infer 1[]{p \land  q \;/\; r}
\end {prooftree}
]]></fr:resource-source></fr:resource></html:p></html:li>
<html:li><html:p>The rule instance with the two premise-arguments <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \;/\; p]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \;/\; q]]></fr:tex> and the conclusion-argument <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p, q \;/\; p]]></fr:tex> is written as:</html:p>

<html:p><fr:resource hash="728c401a911eea5180a9db4bfcf667c9"><fr:resource-content><html:img src="/lectures/728c401a911eea5180a9db4bfcf667c9.svg" /></fr:resource-content><fr:resource-source type="latex" part="preamble"><![CDATA[\usepackage {ebproof}]]></fr:resource-source><fr:resource-source type="latex" part="body"><![CDATA[
\begin {prooftree}
\hypo {p \;/\; p}
\hypo {p \;/\; q}
\infer 2[]{p, q \;/\; p}
\end {prooftree}
]]></fr:resource-source></fr:resource></html:p></html:li>
<html:li><html:p>The rule instance with the empty set of premise-arguments and the conclusion-argument <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q \rightarrow  r \;/\; s]]></fr:tex> is written as:</html:p>

<html:p><fr:resource hash="9cc04d41382335d4ed011af34964378b"><fr:resource-content><html:img src="/lectures/9cc04d41382335d4ed011af34964378b.svg" /></fr:resource-content><fr:resource-source type="latex" part="preamble"><![CDATA[\usepackage {ebproof}]]></fr:resource-source><fr:resource-source type="latex" part="body"><![CDATA[
\begin {prooftree}
\hypo {}
\infer 1[]{q \rightarrow  r \;/\; s}
\end {prooftree}
]]></fr:resource-source></fr:resource></html:p></html:li></html:ul></html:p>
                <html:p>A logic <html:strong>obeys</html:strong> a rule instance if either:
<html:ul><html:li>the rule instance has some premise-argument that is invalid in the logic, or</html:li>
<html:li>the rule instance's conclusion-argument is valid in the logic.</html:li></html:ul></html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <html:p>A rule instance is kind of like an argument, except that where arguments use <html:em>sentences</html:em>, rule instances use <html:em>arguments</html:em>.
So we're up a level now.</html:p>
            <html:p>Also, although officially rule instances can have any number of premise-arguments, for this lecture we will only need to think about rule instances with one or two premise-arguments.
So don't worry too much about going wild here.</html:p>
            <html:p>You can think of a rule instance as setting a kind of condition on logics; that's what the idea of obeying a rule instance is about.
I like to think about it like this: a rule instance makes a demand on every logic that contains all the rule instance's premise-arguments.
In particular, it demands that all those logics must contain the conclusion-argument.
A logic <html:em>obeys</html:em> the rule instance when either the rule instance makes no demand on the logic (since some premise-argument is invalid in the logic) or else the logic meets the demand.</html:p>
